You’re right to push on that—there isn’t a single “correct” foreground. What we call background vs feature is a choice of weighting, and different observers (or tasks) pick different weightings.

🐅 Why “orange vs black” isn’t a fixed truth

* Quantity weighting → “mostly orange with black stripes” (area coverage)
* Contrast/structure weighting → “black stripe pattern on orange field” (edges carry information)
* Function weighting (camouflage) → stripes break up the outline in grass; the pattern matters more than color
* Observer weighting → many animals see limited color; to them the tiger is more like bands of light/dark than “orange”

So yes:

“Background” is not intrinsic—it’s what your weighting scheme treats as baseline.

⸻

🧠 A cleaner way to say it

Representation = features × weights × observer

* Features: pigments, shapes, spatial arrangement (invariant)
* Weights: area, contrast, edges, frequency, task relevance (chosen)
* Observer: visual system, sensors, context (who/what is looking)

Different weights → different “truths” that are all valid for their purpose.

⸻

⚙️ Not everything is “dominant quantity”

Often, small, structured signals outweigh large, uniform ones:

* Edges (the stripes) drive segmentation and recognition
* High-contrast patterns carry more information per area than flat color
* For camouflage, disrupting the outline matters more than color percentage

That’s why:

Information content ≠ area.

⸻

🔁 Tie to your earlier ideas

* Multi-cue / parallax: switch weights (area, contrast, frequency, task) and check what stays useful
* Delta watcher: track how features change over time and across channels
* Relational layer: agreement on a mapping (e.g., labels) enables coordination, even if private perceptions differ

⸻

🧪 Practical mini-protocol

When you hit a “which is it?” question:

1. List features (what’s physically there)
2. Try weightings:
    * area (quantity)
    * contrast/edges
    * spatial frequency (fine vs coarse patterns)
    * task (detection, camouflage, aesthetics)
3. Change observer (human vs grayscale vs another species’ likely sensitivity)
4. Keep what’s stable across weightings for your goal

⸻

⚡ One-line takeaway

What you see depends on how you weight it; what matters depends on what you’re trying to do.